In the face of complexity, many research efforts address a component of the problem rather than attempting to deal with all its dimensions. Interventions based on such sectoral work tend to rely on narrow perspectives; unrealistic extrapolations, untested assumptions and misplaced narratives, and have often failed to provide lasting benefits to rural households.

-KmkPuCPpzu4jz3NA6oq.description:
SSC-Stat is an add-in for Microsoft Excel. It is designed to strengthen those areas where the spreadsheet package is already strong, principally in the areas of data management, graphics and descriptive statistics. 

There are 2 versions available. Version 2.18 is a stable version, suitable for any 32-bit version of Excel up to and including Excel 2016. Version 3 has been redesigned to work with 32 or 64-bit versions, and requires Excel 2007 or later. Please note that version 3 is a beta-version, so there may be unforeseen errors in use.

SSC-Stat is a product of the Statistical Services Centre, University of Reading. It is hosted on the Stats4SD Resources bank for use in non-commercial environments. Commercial use requires a separate licence. For more information, including licensing information, please see the SSC website: http://www.reading.ac.uk/ssc/resourcepage/sscstat.php
-KmkPuCPpzu4jz3NA6oq.name: SSC-Stat

-KmkTM1ssjxOmJiLHSqO.description:
These statistical games assist problem-based training by allowing students to design, conduct and analyse simulated experiments or surveys, within the time constraints of a typical practical class.  
The simulations are engineered to emphasise particular aspects of design and analysis. They resemble cases that may be encountered in real life, which allows us to demonstrate the full process of research and to illustrate a variety of statistical concepts.

There are four games provided. Two simulate surveys and two simulate experiments. They were invented and first programmed in the 1970s. Recent work has updated the games and the associated training materials so that these concepts may easily be incorporated into the MSc in Research Methods at Jomo Kenyatta University of Agriculture and Technology. The game guide describes the games and outlines where they could fit into the teaching. They can equally be used to support statistics training in other RUFORUM universities. A paper written by Kurji and Stern discusses how they have been used at the University of Nairobi.
-KmkTM1ssjxOmJiLHSqO.name: Statistical Games

The goal is to teach users to understand the output from a statistics package and draw practical conclusions from it, instead of simply knowing the process of generating the model.

1497531464103.description:
This is an abridged version of the paper: ‘An integrated agro-ecosystem and livelihood systems approach for the poor and vulnerable in dry areas.’ - Published in food security in 2013 by Van-Ginkel and other authors. 

In the face of complexity, many research efforts address a component of the problem rather than attempting to deal with all its dimensions. Interventions based on such sectoral work tend to rely on narrow perspectives; unrealistic extrapolations, untested assumptions and misplaced narratives, and have often failed to provide lasting benefits to rural households.
1497531464103.name: An "Integrated Systems Approach" to research

1497531878485.description:

1497531878485.name: Conducting Interviews with Digital Data Collection

1497531924348.description:

These interviews were conducted in late Summer 2015, as part of a series of resources designed for researchers of the CRP-Drylands System.
1497531924348.name: The Project Timetable and Comments on the Testing Process

SSC-Stat is an add-in for Microsoft Excel. It is designed to strengthen those areas where the spreadsheet package is already strong, principally in the areas of data management, graphics and descriptive statistics. 

There are 2 versions available. Version 2.18 is a stable version, suitable for any 32-bit version of Excel up to and including Excel 2016. Version 3 has been redesigned to work with 32 or 64-bit versions, and requires Excel 2007 or later. Please note that version 3 is a beta-version, so there may be unforeseen errors in use.

SSC-Stat is a product of the Statistical Services Centre, University of Reading. It is hosted on the Stats4SD Resources bank for use in non-commercial environments. Commercial use requires a separate licence. For more information, including licensing information, please see the SSC website: http://www.reading.ac.uk/ssc/resourcepage/sscstat.php

1497609515605.description:
These statistical games assist problem-based training by allowing students to design, conduct and analyse simulated experiments or surveys, within the time constraints of a typical practical class.  
The simulations are engineered to emphasise particular aspects of design and analysis. They resemble cases that may be encountered in real life, which allows us to demonstrate the full process of research and to illustrate a variety of statistical concepts.

There are four games provided. Two simulate surveys and two simulate experiments. They were invented and first programmed in the 1970s. Recent work has updated the games and the associated training materials so that these concepts may easily be incorporated into the MSc in Research Methods at Jomo Kenyatta University of Agriculture and Technology. The game guide describes the games and outlines where they could fit into the teaching. They can equally be used to support statistics training in other RUFORUM universities. A paper written by Kurji and Stern discusses how they have been used at the University of Nairobi.
1497609515605.name: Statistical Games

This document was written with funding from the DFID Forestry Research Programme, and explores what makes a good research protocol. 

Much of this document is aimed at new researchers, e.g. Ph.D. Students, but parts of it may also be relevent to more experienced researchers. 

The document discusses how best to document different activities at the activity-level and project-level. It is written from the perspective of the statistician and data manager, and suggests that a more systematic and complete recording of planning information can help ensure the overall project is more efficient and effective at meeting its goals.

eSMS: Statistics Made Simple

Statistics Made Simple is an innovative online training programme designed especially for those who are starting their research, or who are involved in development projects involving data collection and analysis.

The programme has been developed by a group of experts within the SSC in response to a growing need for statistics training that focuses on the practical application of statistics. The goal is for participants to learn how best to derive meaning from their data, which involves understanding more than just the theory of statistical analysis.

The Courses

e-SMS is composed of 2 courses, both of which are now run by Statistics for Sustainable Development (SSD) - see our distance learning page for details on the course.

We have also released the presentations used in the course as open educational resources, under a Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike International license. This means that anyone is free to use, download, modify and link to the core materials used in our eSMS course. We believe this is the best way to allow the most people to benefit from these resources.

The Open Educational Resources

Below is a list of links to the different presentations used throughout the entire eSMS course. You can use the links to view the presentations online, or download a zipped version to use offline.
